{
  "texts": [
    "foot_2 Hence, as is already evident from these hints, under the aegis of this term hides a quagmire of ideas that cannot readily be recomposed into a unitary scheme.",
    "This polysemy, to which the term intentionality has always been linked, has the effect of multiplying the positions in the debate on the moral status of artificial intelligence.",
    "In fact, these positions, while appealing to some form of intentionality, do not seem to agree on what is meant by this term.",
    "Despite the complexity of this scenario, one can recognize certain paradigmatic positions that invest the moral status of AI technologies in relation to the notion of intentionality.",
    "The first, represented by Deborah Johnson, tends to identify computer systems and AI as mere extensions of humans (Johnson 2006) or surrogate agents (Johnson and Powers 2008; Johnson & Noorman 2014), reducing technological intentionality to human intentionality."
  ]
}